t5304.text: 9. Australia’s current policies are not scalable. Even if they can deliver the current weak 2030 goal (remains to be seen) they are not fit to drive the necessary three decade transition to net zero emission. That is the policy test that matters.

t5305.text: 8. Targets are important. But meeting targets of any ambition requires strong policy mechanisms across all sectors of the economy that drive change and set appropriate guidance to investors.

t5306.text: 7. The Paris Agreement includes a ratchet-up mechanism that puts pressure on all signatories to lift their ambition, including targets. Australia should respond to this with a revised short-term target before COP26.

t5307.text: 6. Ultimately it is up to our current government to readdress Australia’s ambition problem. This needs to be done urgently. We can fully judge the alternative offerings of other political parties at the 2022 election.

t5308.text: Our 2030 goal was set for a sceptical PM on a promise it wasn’t much more than BAU (but looks like that misread LNG and BAU electric vehicle take-up). The goal ultimately was designed to look like the Obama-era US target, but with a different date and therefore less ambitious.

t5309.text: 5. Australia’s current target of a 26-28% reduction from 2005 levels by 2030 is still deeply inadequate on any measure (with or without the use of Kyoto carryover credits)...

t5310.text: 4. Most economic analysis finds making early and deep emission cuts is ultimately cheaper and ensures a smoother transition to net zero emissions.

t5311.text: 3. No target should be off the table without a full scientific and economic assessment. Ultimately, emissions trajectories are a result of the associated policy, financial and community choices.

t5312.text: 2. It is never a mistake to set evidenced-based emissions reduction targets consistent with a relatively safe climate and the Paris goals.
